There most certainly is an economy on this server.  When I was trying to complete the Initiate Symbol of Tunare quest, I did a combination of /auctioning for the Putrescent Hearts and whacking Ghasts (as it turned out, I got all the hearts by whacking Ghasts).  The people I asked specifically about the Hearts both told me that they were going for 30 platinum apiece (thank you, Yumen &amp; Valquiss).  Well, considering that I had 12 platinum to my name, that was more than twice what I had, and half of the platinum I've ever had in my possession at one time.<br>
<br>
TLC makes some items very valuable--items that only low-level characters can get, that high level characters might want or need.  It also makes some other items more lucrative.  I don't know how many people I see /auctioning in Greater Faydark to make jewellry of all kinds, or banded armor and other forged weapons.  Clearly, some of the trade crafts are quite lucrative.  There's usually one or two jewellers and one or two blacksmiths in Greater Faydark at any given time, selling.  As a tailor, I know there aren't always a lot of buyers, but I get a few now and again, and, while I haven't made bank (clearly, if I've only ever held 60 platinum at one time) doing this, I have turned a profit.<br>
<br>
There is an economy on this server.  It's just different from the economy on other servers.  It requires a lot more than the economies on other servers do.  A common language, for example.  It doesn't matter if I hear an auction for &quot;WTy juzoie of zpoiue!  7 mp!&quot;  I have no idea what it is, if it's being sold or being bought, and whether that's 7 platinum or 7 gold or 7 copper or what.  This has to be a hardship on gnomes, dwarves, and halflings.  I don't see many people in either Ak'Anon or Kaladim.  But that just means it's a challenge to be overcome in order to effectively enter the economy.  And this is a real-world concern, so it furthers roleplay.<br>
